==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|la}} {{term|ablutio}}, from {{term|abluo|abluō|wash away}}.  Compare French {{term|ablution|lang=fr}}.

===Pronunciation===
*: {{rhymes|uːʃən}}
* {{audio|en-us-ablution.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The act of [[washing]] or [[cleansing]]; specifically, the washing of the body, or some part of it, as a [[religious]] [[rite]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1835|author=[[s:Author:William Gilmore Simms|William Gilmore Simms]]|title=[[s:The Partisan|The Partisan]]|publisher=Harper|section=[[s:The Partisan/II|Chapter II]]|page=[[s:Page:The Partisan, v1.djvu/26|25]]|passage=He followed the steps of Bella, who soon conducted him to his chamber, and left him to those '''ablutions''' which a long ride along a sandy road had rendered particularly necessary.}}
# The water used in cleansing.
#* [[w:Alexander Pope|Alexander Pope]]
#*: Cast the '''ablutions''' in the main.
# {{context|Western|_|Christianity}} The [[rinse|rinsing]] of the priest's hand following the [[Communion]] with, depending on [[rite]], [[water]] or a mix of it and [[wine]], which may then be drunk by the priest.
# {{context|Orthodox|_|Christianity}} The [[ritual]] consumption by the [[deacon]] or priest of [[leftover]] sacred wine of host after the Communion.

